<m0>   <m0>I<m2><ql>
<m0>t's getting increasingly difficult to remember that South Florida was once considered a ``cultural wasteland.'' Consider this typical weekend for classical music buffs: Friday night, while James Judd and the Florida Philharmonic played a superbly etched Mozart <m0>Paris<m0> Symphony and a revealing Bartok <m0>Concerto for Orchestra<m0> at Gusman Center, across town Michael Tilson Thomas and the New World Symphony revived Lukas Foss' 1986 <m0>Renaissance Concerto<m0> for Flute and Orchestra and Shostakovich's Eleventh Symphony (<m0>The Year 1905<m0>), repeated Saturday.<ep>
     The remarkable thing is how brilliant (--) technically and musically (--) both orchestras sounded, and how equally perceptive Judd and Thomas were as conductors. Judd's Bartok <m1> <m0>proved exceptional. The <m0>Concerto, <m1> <m0>often spun off by major American orchestras as a dazzling showpiece for glossy virtuosity, had the sort of technical fluency you take for granted because the music-making is so interesting. Judd put a lyric, human face on this score, emphasizing its pungent Hungarian folk flavor and piquant textures.<ep>
    The slow, melancholy opening for cellos, basses, then flute and trumpets was wonderfully drawn, and when the violins came in, Judd made sure they instantly projected the imperious upthrust Bartok indicated for contrast. Phrases and transitions had the articulation and flow of eloquent, not just logical, speech. The winds in the <m0>Game of Pairs <m0>carried on astute conversation, the bursts of humor in the brasses had edge and full impact, and in the mysterious sections (--) following Bartok's instructions to the letter (--) the eerie timpani evoked the subtlest beauty.<ep>
  Judd also captured the ``just'' tempos for the <m0>Paris<m0>, with its little ``all-together-now'' first movement, and delicately shaded and juxtaposed the pert wind and string writing. But in Bruch's G minor Violin Concerto, which Jaime Laredo was originally booked to play, he was handicapped by the substitute soloist, Sergiu Schwartz, whose ripe tone and romantic flair couldn't compensate for spotty bravura technique, a messy memory lapse and far too much smeared intonation. There is a higher standard for Bruch.<ep>
  There also is a lofty standard for Foss, but the New World Symphony met it with Catherine Ransom doing a silvery, round-toned job, whizzing through this marvelously evocative music, which celebrates the spirit of earlier times without abandoning our own. This is the masterly work of an extraordinary mind. Foss' first <m2><ql>
