<m0>movement is especially lovely, with jaunty harpsichord and heraldic brass. But the whole abounds in echoes of Monteverdi, punctuations of Renaissance drum, even ``whiny'' antiphonal strings and flute heard from the balcony.<ep>
  Ransom, about to become a valuable addition to the Los Angeles Philharmonic, was a spotless soloist, and the New World and Thomas took a high-spirited approach to clarifying Foss' enchantingly quaint, imaginative revelries. <ep>
  What a terrific contrast to Shostakovich's Mussorgskyian Symphony No. 11. This music secretly commemorates the 1956 Hungarian uprising, though its program relates the work to a day in 1905 when a group of workers marched to the czar's palace with a plea for help and <m1> <m0>were shot down by the palace guard.<ep>
     Thomas managed an enormously difficult task (--) keeping this huge score's somber mood from turning audiences off. The graphic ``shooting'' sequence does threaten to degenerate into sheer noise, no matter how you conduct it, and it <m0>was<m0> loud and cinematic here. But Thomas couched it within the proportions and meaning of the work, and the dark, brooding expanse of the score was clearly projected without dragging. The orchestra played like a powerhouse. It was a fascinating finale to an often-fascinating New World season.<ep>
