<m0>   As Houlihan & Dancers' performance Friday at the Colony <m1> <m0>worked its way back chronologically, starting with the still-in-progress <m0>Change of Heart <m0>and ending with 1991's <m0>Between Angels<m0>, it became clear how choreographer Gerri Houlihan has changed and grown.<ep>
  There are no valentines in <m0>Heart<m0>, which, despite ironic humor, is a darkly reflective piece. More and more, Houlihan allows each movement its own rhythm and character, creating a strange clarity and elegance. The dancers (--) Ken Benjamin, Bill Doolin, Gabrielle Malone, Walter McLean, Jennifer Nugent and Pamela Pietro (--) are excellent, dancing in silence or to readings of poetry and anatomy manuals, or to Oscar Dorta's pulsing score. (Eric Fliss did the dramatic lighting.) It's sometimes very funny. In <m0>Stress Test<m0>, the dancers twitch through an abbreviated nervous breakdown while a voice reads a questionnaire that goes from practical to philosophical. In <m0>Do You???<m0> Benjamin, McLean and Nugent create hilarious physical puns. A duet for Pietro (--) wonderful here (--) and Doolin is edgy and harshly passionate. <m0>Heart <m0>feels powerful and organic, as if Houlihan dug in and faced up to some lonely conclusions.<ep>
  In <m0>til the cows come home<m0>, Pietro and Nugent play with partnering; Pietro revolves with Nugent on her shoulder, they roll up each other's bodies, waddle side by side, interdependent, challenging, curiously intimate. Now that Malone is leaving to dance with Twyla Tharp, Houlihan might have to retire the 1994 <m0>Chimera (In Your Dreams)<m0>. It's hard to imagine anyone but Malone and Doolin in this emotionally delicate, sensual duet: She floats through it as naturally as dreaming, and she and Doolin move on the same impulse, as if they felt each other in their pores.<ep>
  The gamboling <m0>Between Angels<m0>, with its exuberant sweeping circles and its coy Botticelli nymph poses, looks a little simple and self-consciously constructed now. (Nikki Rollason and Kristin O'Neal joined the other dancers, and Nugent was beautiful in what used to be Elaine Wright's solo.) But it's still a lovely, engaging dance, and an audience favorite. You can see the roots of Houlihan's original voice (--) and how far she's come.<ep>
