<m0>   If you had the patience of Job you had a great time at Steve Miller Band's Saturday night concert, the second of two well-attended shows at Sunrise Musical Theatre. It's not that Miller and his excellent six-piece band didn't deliver their hits of the '70s (--) they did, aided by a superb sound system. You just had to wait.<ep>
      Miller indulged in the blues (--) his own '60s tunes and woeful nods to T-Bone Walker, Elmore James and Billie Holiday. The blues are meant to be gritty and heartfelt. Miller's vanilla voice lacks the range to convey a tortured soul; his rendition of Holiday's <m0>God Bless the Child <m0>was wholly inappropriate. Fans (--) many less than half Miller's age (he's 52) (--) seemed restless. Applause was polite.<ep>
   There were more bugs. Miller announced early that since this is an election year he'd do political songs. He began with the Vietnam-era <m0>Livin' in the U.S.A. <m0>(1968) and stayed in that period for a couple of overworked songs. You could sense a workable theme developing: He could have <m1> <m0>used <m0>The Joker <m0>for the Nixon years, 1977's <m0>Swingtown <m0>for <m1> <m0>Carter; <m0>Abracadabra <m0>for Reagan. Instead, after introducing 1986's bluesy <m0>I Want to Make the World Turn Around<m0> by saying ``We'll snuggle up to the Iron Curtain,'' he quit the theme.<ep>
   After 90 minutes, Miller finally got to his niche: His mastery of catchy pop is unquestionable (--) plunky basslines, tight guitar riffs, witty lyrics, the almighty hook, then get out fast. Here, this material (--) <m0>Wide River<m0>,<m0> Jungle Love<m0>,<m0> Jet Airliner <m0>(--) sounded fuller than on record, and had fans excited (even for a tedious 15-minute version of <m0>Fly Like an Eagle<m0>,<m0> <m0>complete with a rap written by keyboardist Joseph Wooten).<ep>
   Miller is not startingly original, but as the second 90-minute set showed, he's a craftsman who can make the familiar feel fresh.<ep>
