<m0>  It was perhaps inevitable that Friday's concert at the Jackie Gleason Theater, nominally a tribute to Brazilian popular music and Antonio Carlos Jobim, would turn into a celebration of the voice.<ep>
  It couldn't have been otherwise. Despite brief appearances by the great Israel ``Cachao'' Lopez (a token gesture) and guitarist Stanley Jordan (who played one piece, left with guitar trouble and did not return), given a cast of singers that included Dori and Danilo Caymmi, Leny Andrade, Ed Motta, Dutch singer Josee Konings and Daniel Jobim, the late composer's grandson, the spotlight was on singing.<ep>
  Talent was not the problem; lack of rehearsal was. <m1> <m0>The show played like a tease (--) moments of brilliance followed by miscues (--) leaving a feeling of wanting more from these artists, especially Dori Caymmi and Motta, but in a more solid context.<ep>
   With his warm, pillow-soft baritone and relaxed delivery, Dori Caymmi brought the best out of a strong house band that included guitarist Romero Lubambo, bassist Arthur Maia and veteran percussionist Cafe. Caymmi's compact set featuring the unannounced Konings, included classic songs and originals, vocalese, and a couple of Jobim standards.<ep>
   Daniel Jobim and Danilo Caymmi proved a mismatched pair that produced predictably uneven results. Jobim sang in a conspiratorial whisper (as in the classic <m0>Waters of March<m0>) and succeeded. Caymmi belted out songs and gestured as if in a Broadway show, and did not succeed.<ep>
  Motta, a singer with a Pavarotti physique, a marvelous caramel-toned baritone and soulful delivery, went from misery to exhilaration in minutes. He did stumble at the piano at his opening, then turned around and delivered a breathtaking version of Edu Lobo's ballad <m0>Beatriz<m0>, connecting the grit and power of gospel and the lyricism of the best Brazilian pop.<ep>
   Andrade, an underrated jazz singer, got to show off her impeccable diction and phrasing even as she flirted with overstatement.<ep>
