<m0>  Aterciopelados, from Colombia; Fobia, from Mexico; and Heroes del Silencio, from Spain, shared the bill Thursday at the Cameo Theater and offered an intriguing and engaging glimpse into the diversity of rock en espan~ol.<ep>
  In the opening set, Aterciopelados moved with almost palpable relish from alternative rock to <m0>musica carrilera<m0> (a low-rent popular music style from Colombia) to rancheras to a sort of punk folk gumbo. The group seems to be aiming for an ambitious, delicate balance, tempering raw power with humor, adding social commentary to good-time music, cutting and pasting Anglo rock convention and indigenous Colombian rhythms, steadily developing a tight, solid group sound but preserving loose ends and rough edges.<ep>
  Fobia, featuring surprise guest guitarist Carlos Alomar of David Bowie fame, offered a tidier approach to mixing and matching styles, more professional and pop oriented, perhaps, yet just as hard-rocking. The quintet's music, less obviously localized than, say, Aterciopelados', sounds comfortably familiar yet fresh, full of catchy hooks but spiced with quirky bits of psychedelia, perhaps a hint of dancehall, a spoonful of Tejano.<ep>
  Heroes del Silencio, a metal band from Zaragoza, Spain, that has found a following throughout Europe, closed the show with a solid set. <m1> <m0>There is little original (--) or distinctly Latin (--) in what they do. For the most part, they follow headbanging convention, from stage dress to sound. And singer Enrique Bunbury, at a distance a Jim Morrison lookalike, sings in a sort of apocalyptic belting style that brings diminishing returns. Still, for those who wanted to hear metal with lyrics in Spanish, it worked.<ep>
